segments.text: They'd give me some flour sometimes and some sugar and coffee.
I'm a coffee drinker.
And tobacco.
I have that to buy, but clothes, things, I don't buy that.
Well, I buy some meat.
They give me some meat sometimes.
You're about 85 now, aren't you?
Sir?
You're about 85 years old?
Yes, sir.
And they treat me fine.
I don't find a bit of fault.
I ain't had no clothes to buy.
since I've been on the project.
And I've been on it, I think, about nine, well, eight or nine years, I believe.
But I believe.
But I believe.
He was talking about in the old war, time, the old slavery time.
I can remember when
I can remember when the Yankees come through and they carried my father, they carried two sisters and one brother.
And they left me, and I can remember when my missus used to run in the garden upon the Yankees and tell us if they come, don't tell them where they're at.
Told them don't tell nobody where they're at when they come.
They all come and told me don't get scared now and tell them.
who are the years.
I told them no.
He told them no.
And when they come and ask for them, I told them I didn't know where they were.
They was in the woods.
And that was at the house.
And my father, when my father left, he carried, he went away with the Yankees and carried two girls and one son, the oldest one.
Carried them with him.
And they beat the Yankees.
And I can remember that.
And my old missus was named Miss M. And the master was named Mr. Frank Irving.
Mr. Frank Irving.
Did they treat you pretty good?
Yes, they treated me nice.
They treated me nice as they could treat me.
And then after they left, after they died, then I was still here.
I've been here until yet.
And the white folks all been treating me modernized ever since it moved me.
They treat me on now.
It knows me.
They treat me nice.
I came up over here from Mr. Young, from over to Fulton, Auburn, and come to Mr. Young's place up here.
And he kept me there until he died, him and his wife.
And then I come on in from that, on down here, and I'm here yet.
And they all treat me nice.
All the white folks that know me, they treat me nice.
And if I want anything, I'll ask for it.
I was taught it that way by my old master.
Don't steal, don't lie.
And if you want anything, ask for it.
Be honest in what you get.
That's what I was raised up with.
And I'm there to be today.
What's the government been doing for you here?
They've been treating me fine.
Ever since I've been here with the government, they treat me nice.
I was in an old house down there.
They took me out of the old house and put me up there in a good house where they could take care of me.
And I'm in there yet.
I don't find no fault.
any more food to eat, any clothes to wear.
They've been treating me just as nice as they can.
I can't find no fault.
Pretty, pretty happy, then.
Yes, sir.
I take care of the children.
Tend to the children.
Just like, you know, we bring a whole lot of children, you know, and put them down, you know, in one house.
But if somebody have to look over them, you know, and tend to them that way.
That's a house full of little children.
And if you want to act bad, you know, they whoop you.
They whoop you too.
And if the old woman didn't tend to the children, they'd whoop her too.
You know, to make her tend to the children, she wasn't doing nothing.
But she wasn't a cryptic woman like me, you know.
She wasn't a cryptic woman satisfied.
She wasn't a cryptic woman like me.
And they'd whip her.
And they had trays.
I don't know where you see the tray.
Wooden trays dug out, you know, all about that long.
And all of them, you know, would get around that tray with spoons and just eat like that because I ate out of the tray.
With spoons, you know, and eat such as like moisture soup or something like that.
A few of them, you know, before 12 o'clock.
And all them children would get around there and just eat, eat, eat, eat all that down.
And that old woman, you know, she would tend to her.
Her name ain't Tisha.
Yeah, I know that old woman.
Her name ain't Tisha.
It's like slopping hall.
It's just like a tray, you know.
It's just like a tray, you know, you have.
It's made just like a hog trough, you know.
In clothes, you know, they'd wash them things and scald them out for the children.
I didn't see them scald, but that's what they told me, they'd scald them out, you know, for the children.
And them children eat out of that thing, and just with spoon.
If one reached his spoon over in the other's hand, over in the other's plate, he got hit him.
Hit him, and it would knock that spoon back in on his side, on his side.
And that was when we were children, you know.
Wasn't able to tend to no other children.
I had a brother, though, he couldn't tell the children.
And, you know, just sit him down in a corner and put this child, you know how little children put this child between his leg and didn't hold his hand around his child.
That's why he couldn't stand up with him, couldn't, you know, just nothing, you know, shake him this way in the arms.
I can remember that.
I had a brother named Wright.
And he just shake that child, sit him in the floor.
It was too little to pick him up.
Yes, sir.
And if that child kicked much, he'd kick him over too, you know, and the woman would come down, spike him, and get the child back in his home.
And they had certain times to come to them chums, and to come to them chums, and to come to them chums.
Kyle, I say, would go to the calf, you know.
Uh-huh.
You know, they'd have certain time.
Now, Kyle come to his calf at night.
Well, they'd come at 10 o'clock, every day, 10 o'clock, to all them babies.
Them was nice, you know.
Them who didn't nurse, they didn't come to them at all.
The old lady fell.
It wasn't big enough to eat, you know.
The old mother had time to come.
When that horn blowed, it blowed a horn for the mothers, you know.
They just come just like cows.
It's funny, you know, coming to the children.
Out of the field.
Out of the field.
How long did you nurse the baby?
A couple of years?
How long would they nurse a baby until it was big enough to walk, I guess?
Yeah, something about nine months or something like that, you know.
They'd get big enough, you know, to eat.
To get to eat.
And they'd come to, all the time, come down and nurse that baby at ten o'clock.
Ten o'clock in the day.
Twice a day?
Yes, ma'am.
Ten o'clock in the day and three o'clock in the day.
They'd come to that baby and nurse it.
Twice a day?
Yes, and twice a day.
Come there and nurse that baby.
He couldn't eat, you know.
But one could eat, he wouldn't come till dinner time.
But one little one who couldn't eat, he'd come to it.
That old woman had a time of that sort, I'm sure.
Yes, and I knew that.
And I remember, you see a scar up in my forehead?
Kind of scar.
I had slipped out and some boys was throwing and knocked the scar in my head when I was little.
Oh, it's way up here.
It's right underneath your hairline.
Yes.
When I was little.
Slippin' off out there in the old woman's slopping room.
I called it, because that's where it's further.
Yes, and that's called Boy Full of Rockin' Hittin' Here.
When I was young, you know, it hit me.
When I was little.
Coming on out there, I called it old lady's slopping room.
But there's a house, you know, where it fed all the children.
I call that a slop room, where it fed all the children.
Who did the cooking for the plantation?
I don't know what the old woman's name done the cooking.
Miss Clement did tell me here not long ago who done the main cooking.
You know, they didn't cook in the kitchen like that.
They have an off kitchen, off from the house.
Yes, sir.
And then packed it, you know, to the kitchen.
Packed it to the kitchen.
They didn't have, there wasn't cooking in their kitchen, dining room.
I was a very big girl when I know that Mrs. Benjamin had a kitchen and a dining room mixed together.
I was a big old girl.
They cooked, you know, on the outside.
Right in the yard, but no, they cooked it out there.
And then brought it to the house.
Brought it to their kitchen.
when I was a child.
They had some of the slaves who worked in the house and then some who worked on the yard, isn't that right?
No, them working in the yard, men working in the yard some nights, but them there who worked in the kitchen, they didn't have nothing to do in the yard.
And they had one, one, you know, to make up beds, and one to make up beds, you know, and one to cook.
And then they go, they have 60 times, make a bed, and then they go to feel.
And they had a regular nurse, you know.
The nurse, you never did see an old mister with the baby, never in no time.
They had a regular nurse.
It's like, you know, you'd hire somebody's nurse, but be a grown woman nurse.
Tend to that baby.
And we keep them, because never did, never did care to old mister.
Daddy was hungry night or day.
Now, Daddy was hungry.
They carried that to her.
They tended that baby.
That baby slept with the nurses and all of them.
Yes, they slept with them.
Didn't have nothing to do.
Carry the baby and sit there and tell the nurse.
And then after the nurse, you know, then you carry it back, tend to it.
You didn't have to just, she tend to it, you know, and give it to you.
You give it to her and nurse it, how cold it is.
And you carry that baby back on in that room where you was.
Well, did the mistress nurse the baby, or did she have them?
She nursed from the breast.
But see, she nursed this baby after he'd be hungry.
Well, the nurse would bring it to her and let her nurse it.
And then when she nursed, she'd hand it right back, night or day, you know.
She'd take that baby night and day and hand it back to her.
If that baby was any kind of sick, that nurse had to sit up there and night and tend to it.
You never did, huh?
Ma'am?
You never would take care of it like that.
No.
The nurse had to do it.
No.
Well, you see, that's done now, my dear.
That's right.
So it's not done now, my dear.
Well, my niece's granddaughter here, she take care of baby, and her mother hardly ever take it.
And she said, you know, they say you sleep at times.
She never do hardly ever take it.
I know a lot of women do that, don't you?
Don't think of them.
No, I don't think of them.
Well, do you remember any of the slaves being sold?
Do you remember any slave sellers?
You know, men that were just buying sales.
No, sir.
I never did see it.
I sure never did know of that, you know.
We heard talk of it, but then Irene got us after slaves, Irene.
We heard talk of it.
You see them talk about, you know, putting them on stumps, you know, or something high, you know, and beating them off like you did cattle.
bit them off like a deep kettle.
None of your folks were ever sold then?
No, none of them ever was sold.
You were born right there and never did leave?
Born right there and stayed there until I was about nine, ten years old, maybe even more.
Stayed right there.
We didn't know where to go.
Mom and them didn't know where to go.
You see, after she was over, just like you turn something out, you know, didn't know where to go.
That's just where they stayed.
Didn't know where to go.
Turned us out just like, you know, he turned our cattle, I say.
Anywhere to go.
Do you remember when the Civil War was being fought?
Well, I can't remember much about it, but I remember this much.
When Mr. Beckman was gone a long time, looked like a long time, and I remember the next morning when he got up.
Now, don't knock that back there.
Well, we all got up and all of them went to the house.
Went to the house to see old Master.
And I thought old Master was dead, but it wasn't he had been off to the war and come back.
But then I didn't know he was going to the war.
I just knew he was gone a long time.
All the niggas gathered around to see old Master again.
And old Master didn't tell you it was free.
He didn't tell you that?
No, he didn't tell.
They were right there.
I think now they said they'd wait until six months out of that, six months, and turn them loose on the 19th of June.
That's why, you know, you celebrate that day, colored folks.
Celebrate that day.
Celebrate that day.
Missed that line, I missed it, you know.
And just catched it by a wrist this way, you know.
Both of them pushed down in the rocking chair.
And when Mr. Bethany come home, she was crying.
And Mr. Bethany asked her what was the matter, you know.
She told me that Martha Albert hurt her wrist.
And she asked her then, says, what you doing in this house here hurting old Mr.?
She said she wasn't hurting old Mr.
I hope she saw her down.
Well, they took that old woman, poor old woman, carried her in the peach orchard and whipped her.
And, you know, just tied her hand this way, you know, around the feature of the tree.
I remember that just as well looked like to me, I can't.
And around the tree and hooked her.
And what she couldn't do wrong was just kick her feet, you know, just kick her feet.
But it just had her clothes all down to her waist, you know.
It didn't have her plum naked, but it had her clothes down to her waist.
And every now and then they'd hook her, you know, and then snuff the pipe out on her, you know, just snuff pipe out on her.
You know, the embers in the pipe, where you'll see the pipe smoking.
Blow them out on?
Mm-hmm.
Good Lord, him, mercy.
Blow them out on.
Did she scream?
Yeah, I think she was.
I think she did.
But you see, we were glad to go out there.
Well, it was, you know, because our old Marshal was a whooper, and then Uncle Saul.
Uncle Saul was a whooper.
She'd had an overseer, Uncle Saul.
Her papa was an overseer.
But he'd had a whooper.
And whooped her, too.
And then he showed his whip on.
Well, he whooped her so then at night they had to grease her back.
Grease her back.
I don't know what kind of grease they had, but they sure greased her back at night, you know, that way.
They just greased her back.
And so after they whooped her so long, whooped her then so long that way, they quit.
They couldn't.
Gave her her dinner late that evening.
They gave her her dinner.
She was hooked so bad then, you know, she didn't want to eat, you know.
If you put in the hook you had for a day, you ain't want to eat.
Oh, no.
Because a little child, you can hook a little child now.
He'll get mad, you know, and don't want to eat nothing.
So I saw then he was going to hook my mama.
He had a brother, the oldest brother named Cal.
And he was going to hook my mother's boy.
Packing water.
And she's gonna fight him.
Is that right?
Yes.
She's gonna fight him.
You see, one portion of the people belong to Mr. Bethany, and one portion, you know, belong to, belong to his wife.
Wife, you know, just like, you know, you have a lot of niggas, you know, and they give you a portion of them, and your wife a portion of them.
Her people give you a heap of them, and then your people give you some.
Well, that makes two parts.
You got a part, and your wife got a part, you know, of colored folks, by the way.
And so Miss Adeline wouldn't let Uncle Saul whoop her.
That was her side, you know.
That wasn't her nigger.
She wouldn't let Uncle Saul whoop her that way.
Well, then they called her Sassy nigger.
Sassy called Uncle Saul whoop her.
About the boy packing water.
You know, he'd pack water, you know, all day.
And that Uncle Saul, if he stayed late, you know, and when he got to the water where Uncle Saul was, the old seal was, he'd just pitch it out.
Just pitch it out.
That's the chance the children could get to him.
And he whooped him and still let him.
Oh.
Yeah, he whooped him and still let him.
Now, and, uh, and, and, uh, so, Uncle Jesse, you know, he wasn't, Stepdaddy, he wasn't, wasn't, uh, he wasn't, now he's gonna get me away.
He, he wasn't born, he wasn't, he wasn't one of Mr. Beckham's leaders.
He was a Payne's.
No, Stepdaddy, yes, but he was a Payne's.
Yeah, he was a Payne's.
And he'd do anything and he would come with me.
Come with me.
And his head was red and he was red.
Where'd he come from?
I think he come from Louisiana, somewhere.
Anyhow, he come somewhere.
I couldn't exactly tell where he come from.
Because my mama come from Mississippi.
And when he'd back up, you know, I don't know if y'all ever see the corner of him.
Yes, the one in the rail fence.
Yes, yes.
He'd back up in that, and they wouldn't help him.
He'd get him a stick and keep him off.
Yes.
And he was a great big old man, you know.
He wouldn't let them help him, you see.
And the monster wouldn't let him hurt him because he wouldn't let the overseers.
No, they'd whoop you.
The monster would make them whoop you when they see you in the field.
And they wouldn't let him whoop them at all, wouldn't they?
And the old monster would tell them, rather than kill him or something like that, don't hurt him.
But don't kill him, but whoop him.
He wouldn't whoop him, I tell you.
No, he wouldn't whoop him.
No, sir, he wouldn't whoop him.
Well, how would they punish him then?
Give me a year of corn?
Give me a year of corn.
That's like, you know, you give me a year of corn,
And that would be for my dinner or my breakfast.
When we come home to dinner, he said he'd give me air corn.
He said he'd share it often, plow along and eat it.
Just plow along and eat it.
Night comes, he'd give me air corn.
And that's the way they said it, you know, punishing him, you know, wouldn't give him nothing to eat.
And so it looked like he was moving along too slow, too fast with that, you know, too good.
Too good with that, you know, just giving him corn.
And his unit, you know, drinking water and going just the same.
That's why they wouldn't give him none.
Give him none.
Wouldn't give him nothing, you know, but let him drink water, you know.
And he lived just the same.
And he lived with Mama 32 years before he died.
Before he died.
And he never did have a scar that the old boss put on him.
Did he talk like you all there?
No, he had a broken language.
He had a broken language.
Some kind of broken language.
I wonder what that was.
I don't know.
So he was red-red, and his head was red-red.
His head was red-red.
And my sister, we had sisters, you know, half-sisters, you know, to him.
Well, they were red and their head red.
No.
Where did they live?
They lived in Belleville, over in Belleville.
They do?
Oh, yeah, Bellville.
So we ought to go over and see them some day.
Yeah, we go through Bellville.
So we'll go over and see them.
Well, uh, wonder what they paid for this, this, your stepdaddy.
How come?
Well, paid was, you know, he was a payer.
Just to pay them was what he called.
But you see, I don't know what they paid for him.
They bought him, you know.
And I guess he was worth so much they didn't want to hurt him.
Didn't want to hurt him.
And, uh,
You see, he had blown to two sets, folks.
Two sets of people, you know.
You see, he would blow to the pains, then he'd blow to some people, you know, them, but they all stayed with him.
You see, he wouldn't do like me and sell them.
Just sell them, you know, just like, you know, I was a little nigga, you know, I wouldn't act like you'd sell me somebody else.
I wouldn't act like you wouldn't be fighting, knocking with a good hand.
You'd sell me somebody else.
That's what I would do here, baby.
I see.
That's where they done them.
Well, what about getting married?
How did they go about marrying the slaves?
Well, they told me to jump over the broom backer.
I don't know.
They told me to jump over the broom backer.
I don't know.
Well, did they have church?
Did the slaves have church?
No.
I never remember no church.
Mama said, Raleigh Church.
I didn't remember that part of Raleigh Church.
It would have been a tub.
A tub of water sitting just like this thing is, you know.
And that would catch your voice.
And they would have church around that tub.
All of them get around the tub.
Get around the tub.
Old Master didn't want them having church.
They don't have no church.
No, didn't have a church.
And Old Master come along with one of them.
One of them was there having church around the tub, and he's down praying.
And so he's down there praying, just praying.
Old Master come in, he just praying.
He come in, he did, and told him, get up from there.
He didn't get up.
He just prayed.
He said, Old Master, come this way with me.
He quick prayed and then asked me, Lord, have mercy on me, Old Master.
Lord, have mercy on me, Old Master.
Lord, have mercy on me.
I said, with my shoulder, with a bull hook.
He said, have mercy on me, Old Master.
I said, Old Master.
He wouldn't get up and just flinch.
He just prayed for Old Master.
So old Marston stepped back and said, I'm going to mind to kick you naked.
I'm going to mind to kick you naked.
We could have him just stop praying and know he had to go home and live and pray.
He'd go home and live and pray.
Because he wouldn't stop.
Well, that was through the Lord, you know.
That's because of that.
Yeah, the Lord works a lot of things.
Yes, because the Lord suffered him to stay down there and get that hope and then pray.
You know, just keep on praying.
I think I jumped up.
I don't know.
It seemed like me I jumped up.
Johnny, that business of hiring some of the Negroes, the good hands, you know,
Good women, good men, going off and breeding them like cattle.
Do you remember anything about that?
No, I didn't know anything.
They wouldn't let children know that, you know, but I heard it after.
After that, they'd do that.
But see, when they're coming up, they wouldn't let us know nothing about it, nothing like that.
But they said that was sure so.
You know, just like a big, fine-looking woman, a big, fine-looking man, you know.
Old boss wants, you know, children from him, you know.
They just find him up in the house or somewhere, you know, going off and leaving him in there.
They wanted to breed them like they were hogs or horses, something like that, I said.
That sounds like it.
Yes, sir.
And they said that's what they used to do in slavery time.
Did they whoop the slaves much?
Do you remember how they whooped them?
The biggest whooping ever I knew, the gift they gave Martha Albert.
The biggest whooping ever I knew.
Mr. Benson, they didn't whoop his niggas much.
They had to do something like this thing.
you know, bad for him to hook them.
Well, did the slaves ever try to slip away?
Did they ever try to run off?
No, not known on the place where we was.
I never heard them say they run off from there.
You know, old place, I heard them stay in the woods and so long until they'd wear the clothes off and slip up.
Now, I heard Mama say when she was a girl,
When she was a girl, she brought me sipping.
When she was a girl, there was one old woman run off.
She did run off.
The beaters' association run off.
And every night she'd sleep home and somebody would have her something to eat.
And she'd get that vittles and go on back in the woods, go on back and stay in the woods.
You know, just they're telling it over, you know, because you see, I don't know what their name, see so-and-so, ever see them?
Say no.
Well, you tell them if they come home, ring out with them.
Ring out with them if they come home.
Well, I'd be all the way, you know, they'd come.
Say once this man stayed in the woods so long, tell you his hair on him long like a dog.
Just grow up, you know, and stayed in the woods.
Just stayed in the woods.
And they couldn't get him out.
Would any of them run off and get plumb free?
Did you ever hear anybody talk about them?
I hear them talk about them going off, you know, going off to places where they're free.
But here's what I hear her say.
I didn't know that.

She said just like there'd be some white people, you know, would come along, you know, and he'd just get them off, you know, take them, carry them off where there wouldn't be no slave or wouldn't be beat up, you know.
and came off right away.
There was two or three of them that said that white folk would catch them, three or four, you know, colored people off right away.
Peek up the children.
They used to go in wagons, you know, go around wagons with covers on them.
I've seen covers since I've been beaten up in a wagon with covers on them, just take them and go on them.
When I was a child, I seen a little boy, a man jumped out of the old covered wagon
And caught the child.
Caught him.
And got for a bill with the child.
Well, I don't know.
But they caught him.
Caught the child.
And I had a grandchild.
They took him off.
Is that right?
Who took him off?
I don't know.
They took him off.
What do you know?
Yes, they took that child off.
Mom didn't have whatever they wanted.
They took it off.
They took it off.
But they got it at the time.
Well, can you remember what happened when they set you free?
Do you remember what the...
Can you remember how the old master acted?
No, so I can't remember that, you know, can't remember that.
But I remember, you know, time to give them a big dinner, you know, on the 19th.
Is that right?
On the 19th, you know, that's called it.
They said they'd have to give them a big dinner on the 19th.
But now we didn't know.
I don't hide the other side of the folks, you know, we didn't know.
They just thought, you know, just feeding us, you know, just had a long table.
and just had just a little of everything you want to eat, you know, and drink, you know.
And they said that was on the 19th, and everything you want to eat and drink.
Well, you see, I didn't know what that was for.
I just, you know, it wasn't wise like it is now.
Anything a child six, seven years old can tell you.
That's right.
It wasn't wise.
That's the way they done it.
It was a big dinner, Mr. Besson and them.
Mr. Bethany's granddaughter stayed right across town.
And she got a daughter to stay out here in the country, our young mistress.
Out here in the country.
I would have left her.
Have you ever been down in the brass bottoms any?
Yeah, that's right.
I stayed down at the bottom.
I didn't say stay right down in it, but I didn't say I'd wait down there.
I'd wait down there.
I cropped in there.
And when I moved over here, I just moved out of the bottom, waiting right on the banks of the river.
And you don't make some crops down there.
Yes, I couldn't go close to the river.
On account, you know, afraid the horses would get scraped, look down in the river and run off with me.
And I used to plow.
Yeah, I used to work down there at Bradley's Bottom.
On whose place were you working then?
Payne's?
No, I'd been working on Payne's, but I worked then on the book place.
It was called the book place.
Austin, you know, Austin Children, I called it.
I had worked at Austin Children then.
It was called the book place.
I had worked at the Austin Children schools, you know.
And that's where I worked at about four or five years.
Down there on that book place.
